Add support methods for asserting common invariants
# Background
Many methods and constructors have some invariants (i.e. restrictions) on the values being passed to them. For example, an index is often non-negative whereas a power-of-two parameter is often limited to a value between 0 and 63. We should almost always check these invariants (.e.g `requireNonNull(param)`) as early as possible in public methods and assert the invariants (e.g. `assert param != null`) in private methods. This is of particular importance in cases where the parameter is used "later", for example, in a constructor, when passed on as a parameter to a thread or in a delegator.

# Current Support
Java (and core) provides some useful methods for asserting invariants of which the method `Object.requireNonNull()` is perhaps the most well-known. We can also annotate methods with `@NotNull` to state the API contract. There is an optimized `requireNonNull()` in core's own `ObjectsUtil` that is using the intrinsic method `obj.getClass()` (I think later versions of Java will do the equivalent with the regular `requireNonNull()` method).

# Proposed Additions
Support methods and annotations could be added in core as per below:

## Assertions
We could add methods such as:
* `Longs.requirePositive(val)`: Throws an `IllegalArgumentException` if val < 1
* `Longs.requireNonNegative(val)`: Throws an `IllegalArgumentException` if val < 0
* `Longs.require(val, between(0, 64))`: Throws an `IllegalArgumentException` if val < 0 or val > 63
* `Longs.requirePositive(val, MyRuntimeException::new)` Throws a `MyRuntimeException` if val < 1

## Annotations
We could add annotations such as:
* `@Positive`
* `@NonNegative`
* `@Between(0, 64)`

## Example
```
public interface ExcerptTailer ... {
    @NonNegative
    @Override
    long index();

    boolean moveToIndex(@NonNegative long index);
}
```
```
class StoreTailer implements ExcerptTailer ... {

    @Override
    public boolean moveToIndex(@NonNegative final long index) {
        throwExceptionIfClosed();
        requireNonNegative(index);

         ...   
    }
}
```

# Performance Impact
The JIT compiler will be able to remove redundant checking (e.g. null-checks) via in-lining in code paths. Asserting invariants early can in some cases be faster than asserting (or implicitly asserting them by use) later. There are cases where the performance will be affected negatively.

# Conclusion
I think using these methods in our libraries would improve quality and API clarity.

As described in one of my older blog posts (http://minborgsjavapot.blogspot.com/2015/01/enforcing-java-singletons-is-very-hard.html) it is actually possible to create spurious enum constants as well. So, I think the capability to create unwanted instances is there for both alternatives: Enum or utility class. However, I think this is of less importance. If a user wants to create an instance of a class that is not supposed to be created, then let them go ahead.

My argument for using utility classes (i.e. non-instantiable final classes with a private constructor) over Enums is purely based on API management. Adding a public Enum class will have the following adverse effects on the API:

A) It adds `extends Enum` to the class
A1) It adds `implements Serializable` to the class
A2) It adds a `implements Comparable` to the class
B) It adds a static `valueOf(tring)` method
C) It adds a static `valueOf(Class, String)` method
D) It adds a static `values()` method

Other issues:
Some users are confused when there is an Enum with zero elements.
Code completion in the IDE will be polluted with the non-related enum methods (B, C and D)
It adds some extra enum properties to the class definition

So, if we have N classes of Enum utility classes, then we will add an additional of N*3 methods to maintain when ensuring version compatibility. Also, there will be N different static methods doing the same thing (e.g. `Foo.valueOf(Class, String)`, `Bar.valueOf(Class, String)` etc)

A more stringent way of enforcing a no-instance-property would be to create utility classes like this:

```
public final class FooUtil {

    private FooUtil() {
        throw new UnsupportedOperationException();
    }

    public static int bar() {
        return 42;
    }

}

```
This has the advantage of not providing any unrelated API methods and (almost) guarantees that no instances are created. (Well,  there is always instrumentation, isn't it?)

I think utility classes in internal packages (not exposed in the public API) may or may not be Enums.

