Gemini analysis from Firebase Crashlitycs is following

The BadTokenException with the message "Unable to add window -- token android.os.BinderProxy@5b9b1d2 is not valid; is your activity running?" indicates that the application is trying to display a window (like a Dialog , Toast , Snackbar , or a custom view added to WindowManager ) using a window token that is no longer valid.
Cause of the Issue:
A window token is typically tied to the lifecycle of an Activity or a Service . When an Activity is destroyed or no longer in the foreground, its associated window token becomes invalid. If the application attempts to show a window using this invalid token, the BadTokenException is thrown.
In this specific case, piotr_gorczynski.soccer2.InAppMessagingHelper.showVersionTargetedMessage is likely attempting to display some form of in-app message. If this method is called after the Activity that provided the context for the window token has been destroyed or put in the background, the exception occurs. This often happens in asynchronous operations where a callback tries to display UI elements after the original UI context is gone.
Debugging and Resolution:
Identify the UI Element Being Displayed:
Examine the showVersionTargetedMessage method within InAppMessagingHelper.java . Determine exactly what UI element it is attempting to display (e.g., AlertDialog , Toast , Snackbar , PopupWindow , or a custom View added via WindowManager ).
Trace the Call to showVersionTargetedMessage :
Find all locations in your codebase where showVersionTargetedMessage is called.
Investigate the lifecycle state of the Activity (or Context ) that is passed to this method or used internally by InAppMessagingHelper at the time of the call.
Reproduce the Crash (if not easily reproducible):
If the crash is intermittent, try to simulate scenarios where an Activity is quickly destroyed or backgrounded while showVersionTargetedMessage might be pending execution. Examples:
Navigating away from an Activity rapidly.
Pressing the back button.
Rotating the device (which destroys and recreates the Activity ).
Moving the app to the background and then bringing it back to the foreground.
Actionable Next Step:
Implement lifecycle-aware UI updates. Before attempting to show any UI element, check if the associated Activity is still active and not finishing.
Best Practices to Avoid This Issue:
Use Activity.isFinishing() or Activity.isDestroyed() : Before displaying any UI element that requires an Activity context, always check if the Activity is finishing or has been destroyed.
// Example for a Dialog
if (activity != null && !activity.isFinishing() && !activity.isDestroyed()) {
    // Show the dialog
    dialog.show();
}
Expand
Apply this check within or around the showVersionTargetedMessage method. If InAppMessagingHelper takes a Context , ensure it's an Activity context when UI elements are being displayed, and perform the check.
Leverage AndroidX Lifecycle Components: If you're using AndroidX, you can make your UI updates lifecycle-aware by observing the Lifecycle of an Activity or Fragment . This is particularly useful for asynchronous operations.
Pass a LifecycleOwner (like an Activity or Fragment ) to your helper class.
Register a LifecycleObserver in your helper class or within a LiveData observer.
// In your Activity/Fragment:
InAppMessagingHelper.getInstance().showVersionTargetedMessage(this, getLifecycle());

// In InAppMessagingHelper:
public void showVersionTargetedMessage(Context context, Lifecycle lifecycle) {
    if (lifecycle.getCurrentState().isAtLeast(Lifecycle.State.RESUMED)) {
        // Or AT_LEAST_STARTED, depending on when you want to show it.
        // Ensure the context is an Activity
        if (context instanceof Activity) {
            Activity activity = (Activity) context;
            if (!activity.isFinishing() && !activity.isDestroyed()) {
                // Show your message (e.g., dialog.show())
            }
        }
    } else {
        // Defer the message or cancel if the state is not suitable.
        // Example: Add a LifecycleObserver to show it when RESUMED.
        lifecycle.addObserver(new LifecycleObserver() {
            @OnLifecycleEvent(Lifecycle.Event.ON_RESUME)
            public void onResume() {
